Ι will not pause therefore to prove the necessity of a knowledge without which all other is but doubt and pre· sumption. I will only examine, in a brief digression, if this knowledge is possible. Plat0, as I have said, made the whole edifice of his doctrine rest upon it; he taught, accord· ing to Socrates, that ignorance of one’s self involves all ignorance, all mistakes, allvices, andallmisfortunes; whereas knowledge of one's self, on the contrary, draws all virtue and all goodness ⁶: so that it cannot be doubted that this knowledge might be considered possible, since its impos· sibility merely questioned would render its system null and void.
